value.0: Born from the very rock walls they protect, these defenders see and hear all. Massively strong, it is best to avoid these protectors as they will seek out and exterminate all who threaten their charges.
Nemo is an odd little fish. He seems to like shallow streams and people.

A long staff of twisting oak, one in four matching of its kind. The wood originally a fallen branch from the duir, is etched with runic marks that give off a healthy glow you'd expect. They seem to aid in a process of channelling life energy through staves, twisted roots wind around the base in a manner that provides for better gripping, intertwining and sealing into the very end one small piece of coral.  

This is indeed a living weapon, sprouting small buds in the spring and loosing the few leaves that occasionally sprout from it when the colder months are upon it. The staff slowly recharges itself like any plant by exposure to sun and water. 

Having been specifically shed and embued these branches for the selected druid elders, each maintains a perfect display of balance in the abilities it grants the user. In addition, it summons one protector of each of four elements for the druids that the staves deem worthy.
Nella spends more than half her time cleaning herself, trying to be the best-looking badger in the Grove.
Orphore's small black nose wiggles almost constantly as he curiously explores a place he's been over countless times.
If Vichard feels out of place with his human heritage, he doesn't say so, though most assume the presence of Elven lasses more than makes up for it.
Made of a special wood in the Amian woods and enchanted with an iron wood spell.
Small and affectionate, Kessie occasionally finds herself rubbing up against other creatures, or even the legs of some hapless Protector.

Perched on his companion's shoulder, Vorem looks closely at anyone who approaches. His keen eyes rarely look away from the people Naerth so casually greets.
Naerth is the greeter of the Grove, though others often think he takes his job far too seriously. When it's quiet, however, his gaze drifts west...
Isolia is the resident arrow merchant, offering her goods at respectable prices. When she thinks no one is paying attention, she can sometimes be seen moping, glancing off toward the east.
OOC warning: This item is only to be used only by rangers or druids, NO exceptions.
With a kind gaze, Sarin keeps her warm cloak around her as she watches her surroundings. She's certainly more approachable than her elder brother, Elvith.
Usually curled up at Sarin's feet, Whisp lazily looks around, quite obviously fully expecting the ranger next to her to do her job.
With a yawn, Streak tends to feign laziness as he prowls around, keeping an eye on everyone who enters his home.
This old cougar usually stays in one place, preferring to lounge in a tree when Story Night comes along.
Wollhid's nearly constant grunting makes him seem more irritable than he really is.
This boar loves attention, as most find out, but when she tires of it...most find that out pretty quickly, too.
Coalaar, while appearing fierce and grumpy, is actually quite friendly. He enjoys being pet and won't turn away a healthy morsel.

Born from the very rock walls they protect, these defenders see and hear all. Massively strong, it is best to avoid these protectors as they will seek out and exterminate all who threaten their charges.
Typically docile in nature, these wild, skittish herbivores gather in small groupings that scatter quickly when threatened.
Typically docile in nature, these wild, skittish herbivores gather in small groupings that scatter quickly when threatened.

Grace is a large and elegant animal. More of a newcomer than the other animals around the Grove, she keeps to herself. She has a large scar on her left hind leg, indicating perhaps the reason she had been brought here.
Quite the runt, Heera hasn't run off to be a big boar, but he still likes to linger around the others - when they don't chase him off anyway.
A young, playful cub, Cimeria often gets in trouble as he wanders about away from his family.
Dari is a large, lazy grizzly who has a special taste for fish. She prefers to be left alone, but generally seems to be rather docile, tucked away in her corner.
Sass is calmer than her mate, Pip, preferring to watch the comings and goings of the Grove. Still quite skittish, she doesn't like it when people get too close to her.
Pip is known to throw his treasure at people when bothered, but otherwise just chatters away all day, dancing through the treetops.
Julea loves the water. When she's not foraging around the serene Grove, she's chasing Ranni through the stream.
Ranni is more docile than his kind tend to be in a forest - likely due to the protection offered by the Grove. He is perhaps a bit too trusting.
Foxes are best known by their long, fluffy tails, but they are also quite cunning. This one seems to be keeping an eye on the nearby rabbits...
Rocko is blind in one eye, but that doesn't impede his rather friendly nature.

A wild, curious and adventurous young female wolf with a coat as white as pure snow whose eyes sparkle with mischief and wonder. When not tormenting her brother she sets to making the Grove her home and exerting her influence, much to ire of the local wildlife, especially the sacred stag by the Great Oak.

A laid back, chilled out and some might say lazy young male wolf with a coat of light grey whose eyes reflect an inner calm back at those who choose to stare. The mellowed atmosphere of the Grove would seem to suit him for when not being tormented by his wilder sister, he spends his days beneath the shade of the Great Oak.
Aged and well past her years of glory, Daniah remains with the pups. While usually quiet and observant, she steps up to defend whenever the need arises.
A young wolf with a playful spirit, Cairelle greets every person to visit the Treetops. At the same time, behind the playfulness, she watches close for any hint of danger.
This magic bow has a bonus to attack. As well, it allows the wielder to add part of his strength modifier to the damage dealt.
Sometimes caught humming to herself, Tera stands her post next to the others, making sure only those welcome enter the Vale.
Made of a special wood in the Amian woods and enchanted with an iron wood spell.
Arrows of the Vine come with the High Druid's blessing. Upon impact they squirt vine essence and then wrap around and dig into flesh to constrict it somewhat.
Fashioned from rough-hewn wood, this simple door swings on ill-fitting hinges.

Rodlima (rud lee may')

Rodlima is the ninth month of the year. It is also known as the Bird Moon. It is a time for births. The first day of this month (full moon) is when Midsummer is celebrated. 

(Rodlima is from May 30 (Midsummer) to June 27)

Carmoil (kar moy' l)

Carmoil is the fifth month of the year. It is also called the Waking Moon. It is a good time for dancing and challenges. The first day of Carmoil (full moon) is when we celebrate Imbolc. 

(Carmoil is from January 31 to March 1)

Llianth (th ee' ahnth)

Llianth is the fourth month of the year. It is also known as the Poet's Moon. It is a time for peace, creativity, and inspiration. 

(Llianth is from January 1 to January 3)

Bemgusith (bem güs' eeth)

This is the tenth month of the year. It can also be called the Battle Moon, and is considered a time for war. 

(Bemgusith is from June 28 to July 27)

Gidhet (gee eht')

Gidhet is the seventh month of the year, and also known as the Flower Moon. It is a good time for carving and craftsmanship. The first day of Gidhet (full moon) is when we celebrate Beltane. 

(Gidhet is from March 31(Beltane) to April 29)

Oveanh (oo vin')

Oveanh is the second month in the Celtic calendar. It is also known as the Sleeping Moon, and is a time for thought and contemplation. 

(Oveanh is from November 4 (full moon) to December 2nd)

Culendom (cu' lin dum)

This is the eleventh month of the year, also called the Harvest Moon. It is a time of reaping and fruition. The first day of Culendom (full moon) is when Harvest/Lughnasadh is celebrated. The patron deity for the month of culendom is Haskiti.

Culendom is from July 28 (Harvest) to August 27

Duharkat (dwâr kît')

Duharkat is the eighth month of the year. It is also called the Cattle Moon. It is a good time for celebrations.

(Duharkat is from April 30 to May 29)

Shar'tanog (shar' tuh näg')

This is the thirteenth and last month of the Celtic Year. It is also called the Dying Moon. It is a time of sleep, endings, and death. Laknois is the patron deity for this month.

Shar'tanog is from September 25 to October 23

Alverci (al ver' see)

This is the twelfth month of the year. It can also be called the Artist Moon or Raining Moon. It is a time of winds and rain. The patron deity for this month is Basihea.

Alverci is from August 28 to September 24

Haemgild (hayeem' gilt)

Haemgild is the sixth month of the year. It can also be called the Planting Moon. It is a time for growth and emergence. 

Haemgild is from March 2 to March 30.

Hunlidh (hün' lee)

Hunlidh is the third month of the year. It is also known as the Dreaming Moon. It is a good time for resting. The first day of Hunlidh (full moon) is when we celebrate Yule. 

(Hunlidh is from December 3rd (full moon/Yule) to December 31th)
The sun gleams off the radiant dial, the shadow cast marking the time.
The water tumbles into the pool below, the sound of its fall marking a cheerful note.
This rock would seem like an otherwise unimpressive rock, if it were not for the soothing dim white glow that emanates from it. A certain calmness comes to those who get close to the Rock.

Dogma of Rillifane Rallathil:  The Great Oak draws energy from all the living creatures of the world and nourishes, sustains, and protects them from outside threats. Live in harmony with the natural world, allowing each living being the opportunity to serve out its natural purpose in life. As the Leaflord's countless branches, his faithful are to serve as his mortal agents in the natural world. Defend the great forests from those who would ravage their riches, leaving only destruction in their path. Contest both the quick and the slow death of Rillifane's bounty and hold strong like the great oaks in the face of those who can see only their own immediate needs.

Bound in leather this tome looks well worn and the writing on the cover already started to fade.  Still visible however, is the title: "1,001 Ways to Cook Sweetberries".  Paging through the long book, your mouth begins to water at the sound of the delectable recipes.

Dogma of Eldath: Peace is innate and cannot be taught or imposed. Seek stillness and thereby find peace. Plant trees and green-leafed things and tend such things when they need it, wherever they may be. Nurture and aid, and do not restrict or punish. Work violence only to defend, and slay no thing of the forest except to prevent it from slating themselves or another under their protection. Swear to take no thinking life except in direst need. Share with all beings the beneficial things that grow in or come from running water that all may know of and praise Eldath.

Mielikki's Dogma: Intelligent beings can live in harmony with the wild without requiring the destruction of one in the name of the other. Embrace the wild and fear it not, because the wild ways are the good ways. Keep the Balance and learn the hidden ways of life, but stress the positive and outreaching nature of the wild. Do not allow trees to be needlessly felled or the forest burned. Live in the forest and be a part of the forest, but do not dwell in endless battle against the forest. Protect forest life, defend every tree, plant anew where death fells a tree, and restore the natural harmony that fire-users and woodcutters often disrupt. Live as one with the woods, teach others to do so, and punish and curtail those that hunt for sport or practice cruelties on wild creatures.

Dogma of Silvanus:  Silvanus sees and balances all, meting out wild water and drought, fire, and ice, life and death. Hold your distance and take in the total situation, rather than latching on to the popular idea of what is best. All is in cycle, deftly and beautifully balanced. It is the duty of the devout to see this cycle and the sacred Balance as clearly as possible. Make others see the Balance and work against those that would disturb it. Watch, anticipate, and quietly manipulate. Resort to violence and open confrontation only when pressured by time or hostile action. Fight against the felling of forests, banish disease wherever you find it, defend the trees, and plant new flora wherever possible. Seek out, serve, and befriend the dryads and learn their names. Kill only when needful, destroy fire and its employers, and beware orcs and others who bring axes into the forest.

Dogma of Solonor Thelandira:   Walk in harmony with nature and oppose the efforts of those who would disturb her delicate balance. Preserve the wild places from excessive encroachment, and work with those who would settle the land to preserve the beauty that first attracted them. Hunt only for sustenance, culling the old and weak from the herd so that all species may prosper. Like an arrow in flight, it is difficult to arrest the consequences of an action. Choose your targets carefully, for ill-considered action can have long-reaching impact.

The plant where the ever-popular sweetberries grow. Fairly small-sized, these plants have been actually known to grow to larger sizes as house plants, although this practice is rather uncommon. Perhaps due to the fey that usually bother the houses which have the plants potted...

The Sweetberry is a highly prized item for Cordorian children, to others, completely useless.  Commonly stuck on the end of a stick and licked, the sweetberry has a powerfully sweet taste that most adults find overwhelming.  Except in Amia, where they are enjoyed by almost all, sometimes even a little too much, in the case of an ex-assassin who craves them with a passion.
A smattering of arrows can be seen resting in this urn, placed by various suplicants in tribute to Solonar.

Hunt only when hungry and do not gorge without need. Waste nothing and all shall have plenty. The cycle of life links all living things into one being, and that being is life itself. The law of the jungle is that only the strong survive, but they survive best by being leaders, not tyrants, by protecting the weak, not bullying them. All creatures have their strengths in the assigned roles and should be encouraged to find their niche. From cooperation between beings of differing strengths comes the strength of teamwork and community, the strongest force of all. By demonstrating compassion and tolerance and living within the land, all living creatures may find harmony with nature and one another. By staying true to oneself and one's pride and conducting oneself with dignity and honor, the respect of one's peers may be earned. Wemics reduce this to the following: Only the strong survive. Live and let live unless provoked. Protect the pride and all its members, but if injury or illness bring them down, allow him or her a swift and painless end to suffering.

Valued for their great beauty as well as their utility, fey cherry closely resemble the common cherry trees cultivated in orchards, save only for their enormous size. This tree is a small one still, a little bigger than a sapling compared to how tall they can grow. When old enough to grow fruits, they have magical properties. While it produces blossoms every year however, a fey cherry tree only creates cherries once a decade.

Properly tended, a fey cherry tree can live indefinitely
